            <sentence>
                <offset>0</offset>
                <text>﻿The   patient   with   a   presumptive   diagnosis   of   Silver-&#13;
Russell  syndrome  was  first  referred  to  our  department  at &#13;
7.5  years  of  age  due  to  severe  short  stature  since  infancy.</text>
                <annotation id="1">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0004322</infon>
                    <location length="14" offset="173"/>
                    <text>short  stature</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>207</offset>
                <text>His  past  medical  history  revealed  a  term  birth  weighing &#13;
2250  g  [standard  deviation  (SD)  score    –  2.02],  no  chronic &#13;
disease, being able to talk and walk by the age of 2.5 years&#13;
and  has  normal  intelligence.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>439</offset>
                <text>His  parents  were  offsprings &#13;
of  brothers.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>487</offset>
                <text>His  healthy  brother  and  sister  had  normal &#13;
stature, while the height of his mother was 155 cm and this&#13;
father, 170 cm.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>614</offset>
                <text>However, the reported height of the father&#13;
of the patient ’ s grandfather was 145 cm.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>703</offset>
                <text>Physical  examination  at  7.5  years  of  age  revealed  a &#13;
height  of  95  cm  (SD  score    –  5.64),  a  weight  of  12.7  kg  (SD &#13;
score  – 5.57), a triangular face, a low nasal bridge, a pectus&#13;
carinatum,  and  with  clinodactyly.</text>
                <annotation id="2">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0000325</infon>
                    <location length="15" offset="156"/>
                    <text>triangular face</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="3">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0005280</infon>
                    <location length="16" offset="175"/>
                    <text>low nasal bridge</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="4">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0000768</infon>
                    <location length="17" offset="195"/>
                    <text>pectus&#13;
carinatum</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="5">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0030084</infon>
                    <location length="12" offset="226"/>
                    <text>clinodactyly</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>944</offset>
                <text>The  laboratory  studies &#13;
showed  normal  biochemistry,  bone  age  consistent  with &#13;
3  years  and  3  months,  IGF-1  87  ng/mL  (SD  score    –  0.98), &#13;
IGFBP-3 2421 ng/mL (SD score  – 0.61), peak growth hormone&#13;
with  insulin  tolerance  test  after  hypoglycemia  32  mIU/mL &#13;
(normal, &gt;25 mIU/mL), and a normal 46, XY  karyotype.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>1283</offset>
                <text>The&#13;
skeletal  survey  was  reported  to  show  J  sella  and  hyperlor-&#13;
dosis.</text>
                <annotation id="6">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0002680</infon>
                    <location length="8" offset="48"/>
                    <text>J  sella</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="7">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0003307</infon>
                    <location length="16" offset="63"/>
                    <text>hyperlor-&#13;
dosis</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>1365</offset>
                <text>Although  a  definitive  diagnosis  could  not  be  made &#13;
during the irregular follow-up, the clinical picture was not&#13;
considered to be consistent with Silver-Russell syndrome.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>1546</offset>
                <text>Physical  examination  at  the  age  of  16  and  a  half &#13;
revealed a height of 128.5 cm (SD score  – 5.27), weight 26 kg&#13;
(SD  score    –  7.26),  prominent  forehead,  anteverted  nasal &#13;
openings, fleshy  nasal  tip,  full  lips,  malar  hypoplasia, &#13;
hyperlordosis,  prominent  heels,  testicular  volumes  8  –  10 &#13;
mL, and pubic hair consistent with Tanner stage II (Figure&#13;
1  ).</text>
                <annotation id="8">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0011220</infon>
                    <location length="19" offset="149"/>
                    <text>prominent  forehead</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="9">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0000463</infon>
                    <location length="28" offset="171"/>
                    <text>anteverted  nasal &#13;
openings</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="10">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0000414</infon>
                    <location length="18" offset="201"/>
                    <text>fleshy  nasal  tip</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="11">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0012471</infon>
                    <location length="10" offset="222"/>
                    <text>full  lips</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="12">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0000272</infon>
                    <location length="17" offset="235"/>
                    <text>malar  hypoplasia</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="13">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0003307</infon>
                    <location length="13" offset="256"/>
                    <text>hyperlordosis</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="14">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0012428</infon>
                    <location length="16" offset="272"/>
                    <text>prominent  heels</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>1935</offset>
                <text>Follicle stimulating hormone (6.33 mIU/mL), luteinizing&#13;
hormone (1.64 mIU/mL), and total testosterone (347 ng/dL)&#13;
levels  were  in  normal  ranges.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2086</offset>
                <text>A  trial  of  growth  hormone &#13;
(0.2   mg/kg/week)   was   started   following   demonstrat-&#13;
ing  a  bone  age  consistent  with  14  years,  moderately  low &#13;
peak  growth  hormone  during  hypoglycemia  (6.14  ng/mL; &#13;
normal,   &gt; 10  ng/mL),  and  adequate  rise  in  IGF-1  [from &#13;
402 ng/mL (SD score 0.37) to 742 ng/mL, ΔIGF-1 340 ng/mL,&#13;
normal   &gt; 20  ng/mL]  and  IGFBP-3  [from  5510  ng/mL  (SD &#13;
score  1.3)  to  6580  ng/mL,   Δ IGFBP3  1070  ng/mL,  normal  &gt; 400  ng/mL]  levels  with  IGF-1  generation  test.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2614</offset>
                <text>However, the  growth  hormone  treatment  was  discontinued  due  to &#13;
inadequate height gain (3 cm) by the end of 1 year.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2738</offset>
                <text>At that time, a clinical diagnosis of 3-M syndrome was&#13;
made  upon  the  detection  of  unfamiliar  typical  findings &#13;
(slender long bones and tall lumbar vertebrae) in a recent&#13;
skeletal  survey  (Figure    2    ).</text>
                <annotation id="15">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0003100</infon>
                    <location length="18" offset="121"/>
                    <text>slender long bones</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="16">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0004570</infon>
                    <location length="21" offset="144"/>
                    <text>tall lumbar vertebrae</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2956</offset>
                <text>The  indexes  proposed  by  van &#13;
der  Wal  et  al.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>3009</offset>
                <text>were  calculated  in  our  patient:  the  stand-&#13;
ard  deviation  scores  of  metacarpal  index  were  in  normal &#13;
ranges, however, vertebral index of the lumbar vertebrae&#13;
revealed  tall/foreshortened  vertebrae  (SD  scores  of  T12,&#13;
Demir et al.: Severe short stature due to 3-M syndrome&#13;
149 L1, L2, and L3: 2.24, 4.9, 3, and 2.44, respectively) consist-&#13;
ent with the diagnosis  (8) .</text>
                <annotation id="17">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0004570</infon>
                    <location length="29" offset="184"/>
                    <text>tall/foreshortened  vertebrae</text>
                </annotation>
                <annotation id="18">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0004322</infon>
                    <location length="13" offset="259"/>
                    <text>short stature</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>3402</offset>
                <text>The mutation analyses of the patient and the parents&#13;
were  performed  in  the  Department  of  Genetics,  Paris &#13;
Descartes  University.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>3541</offset>
                <text>First,  the   CUL7  gene  was  screened, &#13;
and no mutation was found.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>3611</offset>
                <text>Afterwards,  the&#13;
OBSL1  gene was studied, and a homozygote frame shift mutation was&#13;
found in exon 2: c.457_458delinsT resulting in p.Gly153fs.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>3757</offset>
                <text>The parents were heterozygous for the same mutation.</text>
            </sentence>
